In the general case, there&#39;s no trivial way to make this transformation. For that, review these existing answers:

- https://stackoverflow.com/q/48288988/155423
- https://stackoverflow.com/questions/46753955/how-to-transform-fields-before-deserialization-using-serde

The first is my normal go-to solution and [looks like this](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&amp;mode=debug&amp;edition=2018&amp;gist=8d8eb0efbeec42ca056a5ff3d17ce4b9) in this example.

---

However, in your *specific* case, you say:

&gt; objects with exactly one named field value 

And you&#39;ve identified a key requirement:

&gt; While `Foobar` adds no extra cost beyond `T`

This means that you can make `Foobar` have a [*transparent* representation](https://doc.rust-lang.org/reference/type-layout.html#the-transparent-representation) and use **unsafe Rust** to transmute between the types (although [not actually with `mem::transmute`](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/64073#issuecomment-533039084)):

```
struct FoobarContainer&lt;T&gt; {
    values: Vec&lt;T&gt;,
}

#[derive(serde::Deserialize)]
#[repr(transparent)]
struct Foobar&lt;T&gt; {
    value: T,
}

impl&lt;&#39;de, T&gt; serde::Deserialize&lt;&#39;de&gt; for FoobarContainer&lt;T&gt;
where
    T: serde::Deserialize&lt;&#39;de&gt;,
{
    fn deserialize&lt;D&gt;(deserializer: D) -&gt; Result&lt;Self, D::Error&gt;
    where
        D: serde::Deserializer&lt;&#39;de&gt;,
    {
        let mut v: Vec&lt;Foobar&lt;T&gt;&gt; = serde::Deserialize::deserialize(deserializer)?;

        // I copied this from Stack Overflow without reading the surrounding
        // text that describes why this is actually safe.
        let values = unsafe {
            let data = v.as_mut_ptr() as *mut T;
            let len = v.len();
            let cap = v.capacity();

            std::mem::forget(v);

            Vec::from_raw_parts(data, len, cap)
        };

        Ok(FoobarContainer { values })
    }
}
```

